---
import ContentApp from '../../layouts/ContentApp.astro'

const sections = [
  { id: 'tldr', label: 'TL;DR' },
  { id: 'what-we-collect', label: 'What this site collects' },
  { id: 'what-we-dont', label: "What this site doesn't do" },
  { id: 'third-parties', label: 'Third parties' },
  { id: 'the-pai-os-itself', label: 'The PAI OS itself' },
  { id: 'contact', label: 'Contact' },
]
---

<ContentApp
  title="Privacy"
  description="How pai.direct handles your data: no analytics, no cookies, no tracking — by design."
>
  <nav slot="sidebar">
    <p class="sb-brand">Privacy</p>
    {sections.map((s) => <a href={`#${s.id}`} class="sb-link">{s.label}</a>)}
  </nav>

  <h1>Privacy</h1>
  <p>
    PAI is a project about keeping your AI workflows on your own hardware. This website tries to
    hold itself to the same standard. No analytics, no cookies, no accounts — you can read every
    page without handing over anything about yourself.
  </p>

  <section id="tldr">
    <h2>TL;DR</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>No analytics.</strong> No Google Analytics, Plausible, Fathom, or homegrown tracking.</li>
      <li><strong>No cookies.</strong> This site sets zero cookies. Your browser won't carry any state from page to page that we control.</li>
      <li><strong>No accounts, no logins, no email capture.</strong></li>
      <li><strong>No third-party scripts, fonts, or CDNs.</strong> Everything is served from <code>pai.direct</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>No fingerprinting.</strong> The desktop shell runs locally in your browser and doesn't phone home.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="what-we-collect">
    <h2>What this site collects</h2>
    <p>
      Your visit is recorded in the webserver's access log — the IP, user-agent, and URL of each
      request. This is standard for any webserver and is needed to serve traffic and diagnose
      abuse. Logs are rotated automatically and not used for analytics, profiling, or advertising.
    </p>
    <p>
      <code>localStorage</code> and <code>sessionStorage</code> are used to remember things like
      window positions on the desktop shell, whether you've already seen the boot animation, and
      your reduced-motion preference. This data never leaves your browser.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="what-we-dont">
    <h2>What this site doesn't do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>No user-identifying cookies — first-party or third-party.</li>
      <li>No cross-site tracking pixels, beacons, or fingerprinting scripts.</li>
      <li>No A/B testing or behavioral experiments run on visitors.</li>
      <li>No ads, no ad networks, no retargeting.</li>
      <li>No email marketing list — the changelog is an RSS feed, not a newsletter.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="third-parties">
    <h2>Third parties</h2>
    <p>
      Outbound links on this site (to GitHub, the graphical Rufus tool, balenaEtcher, etc.) are plain HTML links. When
      you click them, you're going to that third party directly — their privacy policies apply there,
      not here. We don't wrap clicks through a tracker.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hosting infrastructure (DNS, CDN, server provider) can see request metadata by virtue of
      routing traffic. We don't share that data with anyone and don't use it for analytics.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="the-pai-os-itself">
    <h2>The PAI OS itself</h2>
    <p>
      The operating system you flash to USB is covered in more detail on the
      <a href="/apps/security">Security page</a>. In short: PAI runs entirely offline by default,
      does not phone home, and does not include telemetry. Model inference happens locally via
      Ollama — prompts never leave your machine.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="contact">
    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>
      Questions about this policy, or something on the site that looks like it violates it? Open
      an issue at <a href="https://github.com/nirholas/pai/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">github.com/nirholas/pai/issues</a>,
      or email <code>privacy@pai.direct</code>.
    </p>
  </section>
</ContentApp>
